I left my wife and
four-week-old son in the US

00:28:56.520 --> 00:28:58.610
to go to business school
in Paris all by myself.

00:28:58.610 --> 00:29:01.920
And she was there by herself
taking care of the baby.

00:29:01.920 --> 00:29:04.430
A lot of people were like,
you are a great negotiator.

00:29:04.430 --> 00:29:07.500
But it's, more importantly,
she was empathic towards what

00:29:07.500 --> 00:29:09.280
I felt was important for me.

00:29:09.280 --> 00:29:10.380
And then she was there.

00:29:10.380 --> 00:29:12.690
And second thing-- when
I started at Google--

00:29:12.690 --> 00:29:14.640
we were in New York as well--

00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:17.020
we had our second child.

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:17.850
Our daughter.

00:29:17.850 --> 00:29:20.910
And then, my wife was
there with both of them.

00:29:20.910 --> 00:29:24.300
And then I moved to Europe
to start my career in Google.

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:27.180
And the same thing happened.

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:29.850
Now both of those
situations were

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:32.650
where she stood behind me and
said, hey, you want to do this?

00:29:32.650 --> 00:29:34.930
Go ahead and do it.

00:29:34.930 --> 00:29:37.290
My colleagues and my
bosses make fun of me

00:29:37.290 --> 00:29:39.750
when they moved back
from the US to India.

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:41.600
They were like, are
you moving to India?

00:29:41.600 --> 00:29:43.140
Now are you expecting
a third one?

00:29:43.140 --> 00:29:44.670
Is that why you're
moving to India?

00:29:44.670 --> 00:29:45.836
It was not necessarily true.

00:29:45.836 --> 00:29:46.450
But, yes.

00:29:46.450 --> 00:29:47.970
She has been there continuously.

00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:51.060
In terms of
mentorship, it happens.

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:53.430
It's not like you will
find the right mentor.

00:29:53.430 --> 00:29:56.950
Having said that, there are some
things that you can structure.

00:29:56.950 --> 00:30:01.050
One is what attributes or
skills that you don't have

00:30:01.050 --> 00:30:02.370
that you might want to learn?

00:30:02.370 --> 00:30:05.130
What are things that you might
want to learn from somebody?

00:30:05.130 --> 00:30:06.717
It's not something
like, OK, I'm going

00:30:06.717 --> 00:30:09.050
to hook this clip to and say,
this is what I want to do.

00:30:09.050 --> 00:30:10.500
Hence, I'm going
to find somebody.

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:13.760
But the idea of continuous
learning-- either from a guru,

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:15.450
or from a coach
or somebody who is

00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:18.450
there who can help you navigate
that next step-- is important.

00:30:18.450 --> 00:30:20.020
You can find them
in various forms.

00:30:20.020 --> 00:30:22.020
And then you need to
continuously look for them.

00:30:22.020 --> 00:30:25.590
The value of a good mentor--
this is understated.

00:30:25.590 --> 00:30:27.529
it's a huge, huge benefit.

00:30:27.529 --> 00:30:29.070
Because they can be
a sounding board.

00:30:29.070 --> 00:30:31.615
Things that you cannot
talk to your colleagues,

00:30:31.615 --> 00:30:34.020
can't talk to your bosses,
because they might hold it

00:30:34.020 --> 00:30:35.900
against you and all of that--

00:30:35.900 --> 00:30:39.502
these mentors actually help
you get the right idea.

00:30:39.502 --> 00:30:41.460
SUJATA MUKHERJEE: We do
a lot of user research,

00:30:41.460 --> 00:30:42.690
and we talk to women.

00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:44.970
And they've said
that the reason why

00:30:44.970 --> 00:30:49.020
I can't pursue a career in
technology, and pursue a PhD,

00:30:49.020 --> 00:30:52.280
and things like that, is because
I can't tell my mom that I want

00:30:52.280 --> 00:30:53.490
to be like Sheryl Sandberg.

00:30:53.490 --> 00:30:53.990
Right?

00:30:53.990 --> 00:30:55.730
Because she's this
foreigner, and it's

00:30:55.730 --> 00:30:58.530
very easy for my parents
to say, [SPEAKING HINDI]..

00:30:59.600 --> 00:31:03.860
So I think it's important to
have these stories from India.

00:31:03.860 --> 00:31:06.650
Role models that, one--

00:31:06.650 --> 00:31:11.060
that inspire us, or fill us
with rage to do something,

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:12.850
like the one that
Elahe mentioned.

00:31:12.850 --> 00:31:14.570
Or things that are aspirational.

00:31:14.570 --> 00:31:16.040
Women who look
like us, but who've

00:31:16.040 --> 00:31:20.130
dealt with a lot of adversity,
and still made it happen.

00:31:20.130 --> 00:31:21.295
That's sort of my summary.

00:31:21.295 --> 00:31:22.670
VINITA SURANA:
Can I add a point?

00:31:22.670 --> 00:31:23.590
SUJATA MUKHERJEE: Of course.

00:31:23.590 --> 00:31:24.410
Sorry, I didn't get your name.

00:31:24.410 --> 00:31:24.951
NAINA: Naina.

00:31:25.451 --> 00:31:27.900
VINITA SURANA: Naina.

00:31:27.900 --> 00:31:30.410
Naina, when you were
talking, every word

00:31:30.410 --> 00:31:32.240
you said-- the choice
of words you used--

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:34.790
is the exact emotion
I could connect to.

00:31:34.790 --> 00:31:35.960
Because it happens to me.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:38.540
Like Elahe said, even
after proving yourself--

00:31:38.540 --> 00:31:39.464
a dime a dozen--

00:31:39.464 --> 00:31:40.880
your parents still
[? laud ?] you.

00:31:40.880 --> 00:31:41.588
They're like, no.

00:31:41.588 --> 00:31:42.440
Why you?

00:31:42.440 --> 00:31:44.320
You know, why should
we listen to you?

00:31:44.320 --> 00:31:47.980
Or why should we listen to
this reverse kind of advice?

00:31:47.980 --> 00:31:51.290
Because like you said, the
conditioning of the society.

00:31:51.290 --> 00:31:54.860
Or they have to go back there.

00:31:54.860 --> 00:31:57.680
And I completely resonate
with each and everything.

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:00.590
But what I can say is--

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:03.900
have you heard of the
theory of the slight edge?

00:32:03.900 --> 00:32:06.660
Just small, daily habits
that you do everyday.

00:32:06.660 --> 00:32:09.020
They need not be important.

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:13.650
But when they add up-- when you
just put one marble in a jar,

00:32:13.650 --> 00:32:15.380
it doesn't make a difference.

00:32:15.380 --> 00:32:18.740
But you keep adding up for
100 days, it'll become.

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:20.900
It will be something solid.

00:32:20.900 --> 00:32:23.720
So taking the points
from both of them,

00:32:23.720 --> 00:32:28.230
that perseverance is something
that we can't give up on.

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:30.200
I our life We want
the best for our life.

00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:33.760
And if it takes for us
to convince our parents,

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:37.160
or have those difficult
conversations with the people

00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:37.930
we love the most.

00:32:37.930 --> 00:32:39.388
Because we don't
want to hurt them.

00:32:39.388 --> 00:32:40.380
We respect them.

00:32:40.380 --> 00:32:42.530
And I think they love
us and respect us, too.

00:32:42.530 --> 00:32:44.090
It's just that
they don't know how

00:32:44.090 --> 00:32:48.590
to have a marriage
of the society

00:32:48.590 --> 00:32:53.460
and the new generation-- our
thoughts, and stuff like that.

00:32:53.460 --> 00:32:55.630
So I feel like in a line,
if I were to have to say.

00:32:55.630 --> 00:32:58.610
is that if you know the
background feeling--

00:32:58.610 --> 00:33:00.410
that they really love
and care for you,

00:33:00.410 --> 00:33:01.850
but they are helpless--

00:33:01.850 --> 00:33:04.190
I think they also
understand you.

00:33:04.190 --> 00:33:11.210
And if you can just have
that in the back of our mind,

00:33:11.210 --> 00:33:15.872
and then go to our
actionable items.

00:33:15.872 --> 00:33:18.080
RATNA SHEKAR: When my daughter
wanted to get married,

00:33:18.080 --> 00:33:19.370
I said, why don't
you go live with him?

00:33:19.370 --> 00:33:21.203
I mean, what is this
obsession with marriage

00:33:21.203 --> 00:33:24.630
and torturing all of us to do
this "Shaadi" and all that.

00:33:24.630 --> 00:33:26.250
But she was like saying, no.

00:33:26.250 --> 00:33:27.840
I must get married.

00:33:27.840 --> 00:33:29.934
So I think your generation
wants to get married.

00:33:29.934 --> 00:33:31.600
But our generations
likely more liberal.

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:34.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:34.500 --> 00:33:35.059
Seriously.

00:33:35.059 --> 00:33:35.725
This is serious.

00:33:35.725 --> 00:33:36.683
Please ask my daughter.

00:33:36.683 --> 00:33:38.970
And she was marrying
a guy from IT.

00:33:38.970 --> 00:33:41.617
And here, we were all
these creative people.

00:33:41.617 --> 00:33:43.700
Because I thought she
didn't know him well enough.

00:33:43.700 --> 00:33:47.150
So I said, live with him for
sometime before you decide.

00:33:47.150 --> 00:33:49.106
I feel if you want
marriage, please do that.

00:33:49.106 --> 00:33:51.230
If you want to meet with
somebody, a guy or a girl,

00:33:51.230 --> 00:33:52.160
please do that.

00:33:52.160 --> 00:33:54.290
Basically, we need to
liberate ourselves.

00:33:54.290 --> 00:33:55.540
This is what my point is.

00:33:55.540 --> 00:33:56.990
Don't say, my dad said this.

00:33:56.990 --> 00:33:58.599
Don't say, my husband said this.

00:33:58.599 --> 00:34:00.390
I've come from a very
difficult background,

00:34:00.390 --> 00:34:02.780
and it's not like
everything was given to me.

00:34:02.780 --> 00:34:04.220
But I just broke all barriers.

00:34:04.220 --> 00:34:05.030
I'm a single mom.

00:34:05.030 --> 00:34:06.960
Brought up two kids.

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:09.535
And then when we started a
magazine, I just went forward.

00:34:09.535 --> 00:34:10.909
It was like an
in-house magazine.

00:34:10.909 --> 00:34:13.370
I said, why should in-house
magazine be boring?

00:34:13.370 --> 00:34:15.240
So just bring the
barriers in your minds.

00:34:15.240 --> 00:34:16.489
That is what we need to break.

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:18.170
NAINA: And then not care
about what everybody says.

00:34:18.170 --> 00:34:19.400
RATNA SHEKAR: Not care!

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:20.330
NAINA: You have to, otherwise--

00:34:20.330 --> 00:34:20.900
ELAHE HIPTOOLA: No, you do.

00:34:20.900 --> 00:34:21.590
RATNA SHEKAR: No, no, no.

00:34:21.590 --> 00:34:22.880
My mom loves me-- sorry.

00:34:22.880 --> 00:34:23.920
My mom loves me still.

00:34:23.920 --> 00:34:26.230
NAINA: When I say everybody,
I don't mean family.

00:34:26.230 --> 00:34:26.922
I mean people--

00:34:26.922 --> 00:34:27.630
RATNA SHEKAR: No.

00:34:27.630 --> 00:34:28.340
They respect me.

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:28.639
Why am I--

00:34:28.639 --> 00:34:30.055
ELAHE HIPTOOLA:
Please understand.

00:34:30.055 --> 00:34:34.540
I am in this work
field, which we

00:34:34.540 --> 00:34:36.179
are looked under a microscope.

00:34:36.179 --> 00:34:38.900
But they rejoice if
our film flops, right?

00:34:38.900 --> 00:34:41.940
[SPEAKING HINDI] We come
from that kind of a thing.

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:45.530
But if you really do
give that much weight

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:48.560
as to what everybody
thinks, genuinely, you

00:34:48.560 --> 00:34:51.080
will not go one step forward.

00:34:51.080 --> 00:34:53.630
And please understand,
tomorrow [SPEAKING HINDI]..

00:34:53.630 --> 00:34:55.159
We're as good as
as the last Friday.

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:57.033
Next Friday, someone
else will get rid of it.

00:34:57.033 --> 00:34:58.330
They don't care about you.

00:34:58.330 --> 00:35:00.280
You think that,
shit, man, they care.

00:35:00.280 --> 00:35:01.880
They don't give a damn.

00:35:01.880 --> 00:35:04.010
I might have won
the National Awards.

00:35:04.010 --> 00:35:05.222
Tomorrow, I am history.

00:35:05.222 --> 00:35:06.680
RATNA SHEKAR: You're
not headlines.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:08.920
ELAHE HIPTOOLA: Yeah,
I'm not headlines.

00:35:08.920 --> 00:35:10.400
Nobody cares about you.

00:35:10.400 --> 00:35:11.730
We think people care about you.

00:35:11.730 --> 00:35:12.980
RATNA SHEKAR: So don't worry--

00:35:12.980 --> 00:35:13.580
ELAHE HIPTOOLA: They
really don't care.

00:35:13.580 --> 00:35:15.538
RATNA SHEKAR: --about
the society, or whatever.

00:35:15.538 --> 00:35:16.954
ELAHE HIPTOOLA: Unfortunately.

00:35:16.954 --> 00:35:18.120
SUJATA MUKHERJEE: All right.

00:35:18.120 --> 00:35:19.890
So that's all we have time for.

00:35:19.890 --> 00:35:21.466
So it's a great note to end.

00:35:21.466 --> 00:35:23.330
RATNA SHEKAR: We should
extend it one more.

00:35:23.330 --> 00:35:25.430
SUJATA MUKHERJEE: But I think
there are some great lessons

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:25.930
to learn.

00:35:25.930 --> 00:35:27.800
Thank you so much for
sharing your stories.

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:29.120
Seize the opportunity.

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:31.000
Show up.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:32.540
Pursue your desires.

00:35:32.540 --> 00:35:34.900
Act from a place of empathy.

00:35:34.900 --> 00:35:37.490
Realize where your
families are coming from.

00:35:37.490 --> 00:35:41.180
But of course, be brave,
and pursue everything.

00:35:41.180 --> 00:35:42.100
Thank you everybody.

